<TEXT>
the cab drivers will still be surly the statue 
of liberty will still light the harbor the bronx will still be up 
the battery down and the folks will still ride in a hole in the 
ground 
but new york is on the edge of a momentous change one that 
will alter the way the nations largest city is governed 
in a referendum that has drawn little attention in the midst of 
a tumultuous mayoral campaign city voters this nov 7 will have an 
opportunity to approve or reject a charter that would strengthen 
the mayor and city council while wiping out an entire governing 
body the board of estimate 
the board is arguably the most powerful segment of new york 
citys government with final say over the budget but the us 
supreme court has ruled that it is unconstitutional so the city 
must change 
i think one of the things were doing is making new york city 
like normal governments in america said frederick ao schwarz 
jr chairman of the commission that came up with the new 393page 
city charter 
that means forming a bigger city council changing the mayors 
duties and responsibilities and creating new ways to award 
contracts approve the budget and myriad other procedures 
polls indicate the new charter will pass easily despite 
considerable if disjointed opposition 
the board of estimate dates back to 1901 it reflected a new new 
york in 1898 staten island the city of brooklyn and what is now 
queens joined manhattan and the bronx to become one consolidated 
city 
each of those five boroughs has a president and those 
presidents sit on the board of estimate along with the three 
officials elected citywide the mayor comptroller and city council 
president 
for 89 years the board has been approving contracts deciding 
most landuse questions and approving the annual budget the 
citywide officials have two votes each while each borough 
president has one 
so staten island with 350000 residents has the same voice as 
brooklyn with 22 million that the supreme court ruled last 
march violated the principle of oneperson onevote 
the new plan is updated to suit a changing new york where 
minorities account for more than half the population but only 25 
percent of the council is black or hispanic 
we paid a lot of attention to making sure that minorities had 
fair representation schwarz said 
the city council would be expanded from 35 to 51 members under 
the new plan and the smaller districts are expected to produce 
more minority members perhaps as many as 20 or 40 percent of the 
council 
with the board of estimate dissolved the council will become a 
true legislature with final say on the budget and most land use 
and zoning questions 
the mayor will continue running executive agencies appointing 
commissioners proposing the city budget and estimating revenues 
a crucial element in spending debates 
what the citys doing is moving from a unique screwball form 
of government to one that looks a lot more like what other cities 
do thats a strong mayor strong council form of government 
said gene russianoff attorney for the new york public interest 
research group 
supporters say the larger council and new requirements for 
public disclosure and a new independent budget office will check 
the mayors power 
but without the board of estimate critics contend the mayor 
will be too powerful we will have an imperial mayor said 
ralph j lamberti borough president of staten island 
lamberti and his fellow borough presidents stand to lose the 
most power under the plan and are among its most outspoken 
opponents the other opponents come from a variety of sources that 
dont necessarily have much else in common 
theres the far left and the far right and were sort of the 
center schwarz said these people are utterly strange 
bedfellows they couldnt possibly come up with a solution 
most city residents seem only vaguely aware of the proposed 
changes which arent after all going to revolutionize life in 
new york 
the average resident schwarz said is going to find 
government more responsive and that will be a plus but will it 
pave the streets with gold no 
</TEXT>
