<TEXT>
investigators found a trail 
leading to malta as the likely source of the bomb that blew up pan 
am flight 103 over scotland killing 270 people prosecutors 
spokesman jochen schroers said monday 
authorities said a libyan man may have played a role in the dec 
21 bombing 
schroers of the prosecutors office said a suitcase coming 
from malta aboard an air malta flight was the presumed 
container for the bomb 
the suitcase was put aboard the air malta flight on the tiny 
mediterranean island nation before being transferred to the pan am 
flight at its originating point in frankfurt officials reported 
other evidence recently uncovered by investigators in europe 
adds to suspicion that the bombing was carried out by the popular 
front for the liberation of palestinegeneral command the new york 
times reported in its tuesday editions 
sixteen members of the palestinian group were arrested in raids 
in west germany in october 1988 and a bomb similar to the one 
believed to have destroyed the plane was seized in that 
investigation us officials told the times that mohammed abu 
talb a palestinian now being held on terrorism charges in sweden 
has told investigators he retrieved one bomb overlooked in the 
raids and passed it to another person 
officials declined to identify to whom talb said he passed the 
bomb but they also said talb was spotted in malta in october 1988 
in the company of hafez dalkamoni a suspected leader of the 
palestinian group who was arrested in the west german raids later 
that month 
londons sunday times first disclosed the evidence of a possible 
maltese connection it said the bomb was placed in a suitcase 
containing clothing made and purchased in malta 
citing british sources the newspaper said the baggage list 
showed one suitcase was transferred to flight 103 from air malta 
flight km180 which originated in malta on the morning of dec 21 
no passenger accompanied the bag on the pan am flight it said 
all 259 people on the jumbo jet and 11 residents of lockerbie 
scotland died as a result of the dec 21 bombing 
in a statement sent by fascimile machine to news media schroers 
said west german investigators earlier informed scottish 
investigators about suspicions regarding malta 
the suspicions were made more concrete when the scottish 
officials informed the germans that clothing made in malta was in 
the presumed bomb suitcase the statement said 
it said passengers on the air malta flight were not under 
suspicion 
the statement denied british news media reports of friction 
between west german and british investigators 
schroers said earlier in a telephone interview with the 
associated press that west german investigators are in malta but 
the scottish officials are taking the lead 
it was possibly a man of libyan extraction but we cant say 
more than that schroers said of the person who investigators 
believe bought the clothes that were in the suitcase 
the investigation into this lead has not been completed 
previous reports said the bomb was placed on board in luggage 
checked in at frankfurt west german investigators repeatedly 
denied any evidence existed to substantiate those claims 
pan am flight 103 originated in frankfurt taking on passengers 
and luggage flown in from other areas on international feeder 
flights passengers and bags were transferred to the doomed 
boeing 747 at heathrow airport in london 
willi fundermann a spokesman for the federal criminal 
investigations office in wiesbaden said investigators have a hot 
trail leading to malta 
there are clues that a suitcase from malta may have played a 
part said fundermann 
there are also clues that someone from libya or at least 
someone with a libyan accent may have bought the items 
the flight 103 bomb was packed into a toshiba radiocassette 
player investigators have said 
malta about 180 miles north of libya enjoys good relations 
with the government of radical leader col moammar gadhafi in 
tripoli 
in scotland the chief investigator and head of the judiciary 
both refused monday to disclose any details of the hunt for the 
bomber 
george esson chief constable of dumfries and galloway who is 
leading the international investigation issued a statement saying 
investigators are pursuing a number of encouraging lines of 
inquiry in a number of countries 
lord fraser scotlands lord advocate and its top judicial 
officer said in a separate statement that the investigation 
continues to make encouraging progress he said he feared that 
premature disclosure of the progress of the investigation could 
cause grave prejudice to the investigation itself 
esson said since the outset of this inquiry there has been a 
close liaison between the scottish police the fbi and the bka 
information exchanged at regular meetings between these three 
agencies has contributed greatly to the ongoing and very active 
criminal investigation 
