<TEXT>
before solidarity took power in poland jan 
nowak was the communist governments enemy no 1 because for 24 
years he headed the polish section of radio free europe the 
ussponsored radio station that beams into the soviet bloc 
when nowak returned to warsaw aug 28 for his first visit since 
1945 he was stunned to find the airport crammed with senior 
solidarity leaders they took time out from forming the first 
noncommunist government in the soviet bloc to welcome him as a 
hero 
lech walesa called nowaks return a visible symbol of 
change said nowak and his warm reception was symbolic of an 
improved status for radio free europe and radio liberty behind the 
crumbling iron curtain 
the stations were created in 1950 and 1951 during the cold war 
and despite their ups and downs over the years are thriving in the 
current thaw nowak headed the polish section for 24 years starting 
in 1951 
official polish television which formerly condemned the 
socalled foreign voices that carried news censored from 
staterun media not only reported nowaks triumphant return it 
broadcast an interview with him 
when nowak stepped out the next day to take a nostalgic walk 
through the city i had not visited for 45 years a taxi driver 
veered over took him around town and refused to accept payment 
the driver told me he had seen the airport arrival on 
television he said i listened to radio free europe for so many 
years without paying anything how can i take money from you 
nowak 76 recalled during an interview after he returned to his 
home near washington 
like nowak radio free europe and its sister station radio 
liberty are enjoying their new role not only in poland but in the 
soviet union and other countries of the communist bloc 
it has become a very exciting place to be the radios are 
on the cutting edge of the changes underway in the soviet bloc 
said gene pell a former nbctv correspondent who now directs the 
twin radio stations 
the stations were founded by the central intelligence agency 
and in 1971 after revelations of cia misdeeds were separated from 
the spy agency and funded by congress 
congressional reports requested by the senate foreign relations 
committee in 198485 criticized the stations for sometimes 
broadcasting material considered abusive of communist and 
government officials in the soviet bloc 
since pell took over in november 1985 said a foreign relations 
committee aide he has done a fine job in curbing the problems we 
saw four years ago 
but media in the soviet bloc continued to depict the voices 
as branches of the cia jammed their broadcasts to major cities 
and bitterly condemned emigres like nowak who worked for them 
nevertheless the stations had an audience estimated at 50 
million according to the 1985 congressional report 
under the reforms launched since then by soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev the vituperation has ended and the audience 
has expanded 
the major breakthrough was in november of last year when they 
turned the jammers off pell said in a recent interview in 
washington 
taking advantage of the thaw radio liberty which broadcasts to 
the soviet union has hired reporters in moscow leningrad kiev 
and novosibirsk said pell who was the nbc correspondent in moscow 
in the late 1970s when most soviets feared speaking with 
westerners and could receive prison sentences of up to seven years 
for listening to radio liberty and radio free europe 
radio free europe which broadcasts to the rest of the soviet 
bloc has received permission to open an office in hungary and 
wants a bureau in warsaw 
official press criticisms have tapered off and the weekly 
moscow news last year praised radio libertys coverage of the 
december 1988 earthquake in armenia calling it better than radio 
moscows 
in this case we heard on a foreign band what we should have 
heard on our own vladimir ostrogorsky wrote in the dec 18 
1988 moscow news 
although ostrogorsky said the voices in the past had 
broadcast rumors misrepresentations and outright lies and had 
pushed their own ideological goods packaged as information he 
praised the end of the jamming as testimony to the progress of 
glasnost or greater openness 
pell said simultaneously another thing happened the most 
significant of all the place opened up we could call people they 
could call us 
broadcasters in munich tape reports from throughout the soviet 
bloc and transmit them back in 
we now have a broadcast called at the kiosk in which our 
moscow correspondent reads excerpts from press reports the same day 
they are published said pell the show is popular because the 
most interesting newspapers sell out quickly even in major cities 
and may not be available at all elsewhere 
</TEXT>
