<TEXT>
a decline in us oats production is prompting 
congress to look into the situation and agriculture department 
analysts say consumer demand for oatmeal is one of the many factors 
for consideration 
some believe the governments price support program for oats 
should be modified to encourage farmers to plant more oats instead 
of turning to other feed grains such as barley corn or sorghum 
whatever remedies are forthcoming the united states since 1982 
has been a net importer of oats instead of an exporter canada 
sweden finland and argentina are the major foreign suppliers 
the us market share of all world oats imports rose to an 
annual average of 44 percent in 198588 largest of all importing 
countries says the departments economic research service 
the agency in a new staff report prepared as background for 
1990 farm legislation said oats are grown in most states but are 
concentrated in the north central region including the dakotas 
minnesota iowa and nebraska 
in the 1950s oats were grown on more than 40 million acres and 
annual farm prices averaged 58 cents to 72 cents per bushel in 
recent years oats have been produced on 6 million to 10 million 
acres with farm prices climbing from 121 per bushel in 1986 to 
156 in 1987 and a record 267 in 1988 
the value of oats production in 1987 ranked 16th among major 
us field crops at 606 million by comparison corn was 14 
billion soybeans 113 billion hay 9 billion and wheat 55 
billion 
the principal domestic use of oats is for livestock feed 
although it has recently become a specialty feed for race and 
pleasure horses the report said 
oats as human food includes the traditional oatmeal along with 
oat flour natural cereals meat product extenders cookies and 
breads granola oat bran and baby food 
recent medical research has shown that certain fibrous plant 
materials in the diet can lower serum cholesterol concentrations 
the report said the fibers however must be water soluble oat 
bran is water soluble but wheat bran is not watersoluble dietary 
fibers also lower postmeal blood glucose levels in 
insulindependent diabetics 
the report added thus oat bran or whole oats is beginning to 
play a larger role in improving health through diet oats 
consumption by humans appears to be increasing as us diets seem 
to be shifting toward cerealbased foods and away from fatty 
highprotein animalbased foods 
