<TEXT>
agriculture department scientists say they 
have developed a new lethal snack for cockroaches grasshoppers 
crickets and fire ants that smells too yummy to resist 
the bait includes corn mash left over from the manufacture of 
fuelgrade alcohol ethanol and a waterabsorbent gel the mixture 
is laced with a slowrelease insecticide 
according to the departments agricultural research service the 
new bait was initially designed to use against cockroaches but 
researchers at the agencies insect laboratory in gainesville fla 
found it attracted the other species too 
entomologist richard j brenner said the combination of corn 
mash and gel tends to retain moisture and remains aromatic under 
high temperatures and dry conditions that makes it particularly 
attractive to roaches which become hungry and thirsty when the 
temperature rises 
the bait has been tested in the field as well as in the 
laboratory and is waiting on approval by the environmental 
protection agency he said 
although the mashgel combination was developed by brenner and 
an agency colleague richard s patterson there are two other 
coinventors roger r pierce of pierce services inc cashier 
nc and marvin hult of air vent inc peoria ill 
air vent and pierce services signed research agreements with the 
usda agency in february 1988 and hold first rights to license the 
bait when a patent is granted 
pierce to protect the baits aroma and moisture during storage 
suggested wrapping the bait in wax film that a hungry cockroach can 
open easily hult recommended using a bait holder which would 
extend the shelf life of the mixture and protect it until ready for 
use 
brenner said that while the corn mash attracts roaches hoppers 
crickets and fire ants it doesnt attract warmblooded animals as 
do baits of fruit bread raisins or beer 
