the report said the bomb was transferred from a malta flight to 
flight 103 in frankfurt inside a suitcase unaccompanied by a 
passenger 
the newspaper which quoted airline personnel in malta also 
reported sunday that the suitcase carried clothing purchased in 
malta it said investigators had traced the clothing to a store 
where the shopkeeper remembered that a man he believed was libyan 
had bought them 
today a spokesman for west germanys federal criminal 
investigations office in wiesbaden confirmed the maltese link and 
said it was providing a hot trail for investigators 
the scottish detectives who are heading the investigation have 
contended for several months that the bomb was put on the jet in 
frankfurt where flight 103 originated passengers and luggage were 
transferred to a boeing 747 at heathrow airport in london 
all 259 people aboard and 11 residents on the ground were killed 
when the bomb ripped apart the jet over lockerbie scotland on 
dec 21 
there are clues that a suitcase from malta may have played a 
part said willi fundermann a spokesman for the federal 
investigations office 
there are also clues that someone from libya or at least 
someone with a libyan accent may have bought the items of 
clothing whether he also is the one who brought it the suitcase 
on board is still not known at this time fundermann said in a 
telephone interview 
scottish authorities have declined comment on any malta 
connection 
no one has been charged in the bombing 
there has long been speculation that a group of palestinians 
arrested in october in west germany may have been behind the 
attack but fundermann said there was no proof of that 
he said the initial clue about a malta connection came from an 
examination of the remains from the crash site he did not 
elaborate 
the sunday times said the evidence was in a computer list of all 
luggage put aboard flight 103 in frankfurt 
