challenged both by korean air lines and a philadelphia man replaced 
in his kal job by a korean citizen 
justice byron r white voted to hear arguments in the case but 
four votes are needed to grant such review 
thomas v macnamara was fired in 1982 as kals 
philadelphiabased district sales manager for delaware 
pennsylvania and southern new jersey he was replaced by wan gin 
chung who is in this country on a visa 
macnamara said the airline violated that portion of the civil 
rights act of 1964 banning discrimination based on race or national 
origin 
macnamara 57 when he was fired also said kal violated a 
federal law against age bias chung was 42 in 1982 
the 3rd us circuit court of appeals in its ruling last 
december gave partial victories to both macnamara and kal 
the appeals court ordered that macnamaras lawsuit go to trial 
but said he could prevail only if proving kal intentionally 
discriminated against him based on some illegal criterion 
the appeals court said that to win macnamara must prove that 
kal would not have fired him but for his race national origin or 
age 
macnamara cannot succeed by showing primarily with statistical 
evidence that his firing had the effect of discriminating against 
older white americans the appeals court said 
the 3rd circuit court rejected kals argument that it should be 
shielded from all bias suits because of a 1956 treaty of 
friendship commerce and navigation between the united states and 
korea 
the treaty gives businesses of each nation broad discretion in 
hiring on foreign soil 
the appeals court said the treatys limited purpose is to 
assure foreign investors the freedom to place their own citizens 
in key management positions thus facilitating their operational 
success in the host country 
the treaty does not authorize a broad exemption from laws that 
prohibit discrimination on grounds unrelated to citizenship the 
appeals court said 
kal lawyers said the ruling will discourage foreign investment 
in the united states and american investment abroad 
macnamara said the decision gives foreign corporations greater 
rights than those of domestic us corporations and exposes us 
workers to discrimination 
the bush administration urged the supreme court to reject the 
competing appeals 
the cases are kal vs macnamara 881449 and macnamara vs kal 
881551 
