<TEXT>
the supreme court today left intact a 425 
million award to the families of five navy divers killed in an 
accident aboard the submarine uss grayback in the philippines seven 
years ago 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by general 
dynamics corp designer of the diving chamber in which the men 
died 
the accident occurred near subic bay the night of jan 16 1982 
when the divers were trapped inside the diving chamber without 
adequate air 
a ventilation valve that allows air to enter the flooded chamber 
was not fully open creating a vacuum as the water drained 
the victims were william robinson of cassopolis mich richard 
bond of bremerton wash charles bloomer of middleton ky rodney 
fitz of hixson tenn and leslie shelton of goldsboro nc 
the grayback originally a missilecarrying sub was converted 
in the late 1960s to dispatch divers underwater 
general dynamics designed the diving chamber which then was 
built by the navy 
court records said the navy was aware of a problem with the 
ventilation valve it was difficult to turn and there were no 
warning devices to tell the divers it was not open completely 
but the sub operated safely for 13 years as the navy rather 
than redesigning the system chose to compensate for the problem by 
training divers to cope 
a federal judge in texas ordered general dynamics to pay 425 
million to the victims families the navy was not ordered to pay 
any money 
the 5th us circuit court of appeals upheld the damage judgment 
in february 
the appeals court interpreting a key 1988 supreme court ruling 
refused to shield general dynamics from the award 
the high court last year ruled that a military contractor is 
protected from being sued when the government approves equipment 
conforming to reasonably precise pentagon specifications and 
the company warns the government about any potential dangers of 
which it is aware 
the 5th circuit court said that ruling does not protect general 
dynamics because the navy in effect rubberstamped the 
contractors design plans thus the appeals court said it was the 
company rather than the navy that exercised discretion over the 
chambers design 
the government does not exercise a discretionary function by 
merely approving the contractors work the appeals court said 
if the government delegates its design discretion to the 
contractor and allows the contractor to develop the design the 
government contractor defense against being sued does not apply 
major military contractors and business groups joined general 
dynamics in urging the supreme court to overturn the 5th circuit 
court ruling 
the us chamber of commerce said the appeals court ruling 
undermines the 1988 supreme court decision and could discourage 
companies from competing for military contracts 
the case is general dynamics vs trevino 89376 
</TEXT>
