at forcing all manufacturers of the drug to share in paying damages 
for injuries allegedly caused by des 
des the common name for the synthetic female hormone 
diethylstilbestrol was made and sold by some 300 phramaceutical 
companies from 1947 until 1971 
up to 3 million women used it to help prevent miscarriages but 
in 1970 researchers discovered a connection between des and cancer 
in the daughters of women who used the drug 
there was evidence the cancer often did not develop until the 
daughter of the des user was from 15 to 25 years old 
in the cases acted on today er squibb amp sons eli lilly and 
co and rexall drug co challenged a ruling last april by the new 
york court of appeals 
the state court said it is generally impossible to identify the 
manufacturer of the des ingested in any particular case 
druggists usually filled prescriptions from whatever was on hand 
and one brand of des pretty much resembled the next the state 
court said 
also it said because years or decades passed before the cancer 
developed it is practically impossible to trace the producer of 
des in any particular case 
the state court rejected manufacturers claims that they should 
not be held liable for potentially millions of dollars in damages 
when there is no proof they made the drug that caused any injury 
but the appeals court said 
it would be inconsistent with the reasonable expectations of a 
modern society to say to these women that because of the 
insidious nature of an injury that long remains dormant and 
because so many manufacturers each behind a curtain contributed 
to the devastation the cost of injury should be borne by the 
innocent and not the wrongdoers 
the state court said damage awards against each company should 
be paid based on its percentage of national des sales 
this socalled market theory corresponds to the overall 
culpability of each defendant measured by the amount of risk of 
injury each defendant created to the public at large the state 
court said 
that court also upheld a 1986 new york law that suspended the 
deadline for filing damage claims allegedly caused by des the law 
permitted suits to be filed for one year regardless of when the 
injury occurred 
because of the latent nature of des injuries we believe that 
an injustice has been rectified by creating the oneyear 
window the state court said 
the cases are rexall drug co vs tigue 89168 er squibb amp 
sons vs hymowitz 89204 eli lilly vs hymowitz 89397 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

