the justices without comment let stand a ruling that a 
moorestown nj man accused of numerous motor vehicle offenses 
was arrested unlawfully in his home two years ago 
richard j bolte was arrested at his home in the predawn hours 
of april 6 1987 
police officer william liss had followed a car he noticed 
swerving on and off the road he tried to pull the car over by 
activating his squad cars lights and siren 
the swerving car ignored the officers signals and made four 
loops through a residential neighborhood before pulling into a 
private driveway and into a garage 
liss stopped his car in the driveway and ran into the garage he 
told bolte to stop but bolte entered the house liss followed him 
telling bolte that he was under arrest 
when taken to a police station bolte refused to take a 
breathalyzer test he was charged with reckless driving driving 
while intoxicated refusal to submit to a breathalyzer test 
driving with an expired license failure to maintain a single lane 
eluding and resisting arrest and disorderly conduct 
bolte sought to have his refusal to submit to a breath test 
thrown out as trial evidence claiming that it was based on an 
unlawful arrest 
a trial judge turned down boltes request but a state appeals 
court and the new jersey supreme court ruled that the evidence must 
be suppressed 
the states highest court ruled that boltes warrantless arrest 
in his home amounted to an unreasonable police seizure banned by 
the constitutions fourth amendment 
in the appeal acted on today new jersey attorney general peter 
perretti relied on previous rulings in which the justices allowed 
such warrantless arrests in cases of hot pursuit by police of 
criminal suspects 
but the new jersey court said the hotpursuit exception to the 
fourth amendments warrant requirement has been interpreted to 
apply only to the pursuit of fleeing felons not people 
suspected of relatively minor crimes or misdemeanors 
the case is new jersey vs bolte 89417 
