maine couples heavily wooded property 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that officers 
violated the couples privacy rights when they entered the grounds 
without a search warrant 
the appeal stems from a search by officers from the kennebec 
county sheriffs department of paul wings 45acre property in 
litchfield maine on aug 19 1987 patricia magagnoli lived there 
with wing 
the officers after getting a tip that marijuana was being grown 
in the area flew over it in an airplane and spotted what they 
believed to be marijuana plants in a grassy clearing 
without a court warrant they entered wings property using a 
driveway that splits into a y about 100 feet from the road the 
left leg of the driveway leads to wings home and the right ends at 
a grassy area where the officers said they discovered the marijuana 
the grassy area turned out not to be the same clearing the 
officers observed from the airplane that clearing was on a 
neighbors property where marijuana also was growing 
the officers got a warrant before seizing the marijuana plants 
and searching the home where wing and ms magagnoli lived 
a state judge ruled the plants could not be used as evidence 
against the couple the judge said wing preserved the heavily 
wooded nature of the property to guard his privacy in effect using 
trees as a substitute for a fence 
the judge emphasized that wing and ms magagnoli said they 
sunbathed in the nude and made love in the grassy clearing the 
couple reasonably expected their intimate activities there 
would be as private as if they took place in the home the judge 
said 
the ruling was upheld by a 33 vote of the maine supreme 
judicial court last june 
maine prosecutors said the judges decision conflicts with a 
1987 supreme court ruling that allowed police without a warrant to 
enter fencedin but unwooded property and look into a barn 
located about 60 yards from a ranch house 
the justices ruled in that case that the barn was not part of 
the homeowners curtilage the area of land occupied by a 
dwelling its yard and other nearby buildings that are protected 
against warrantless searches by the constitutions fourth amendment 
the high court in 1984 reaffirmed a longstanding legal doctrine 
that police may enter and search even fencedin open fields 
without a court warrant 
the case acted on today is maine vs wing 89381 
