<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to review a 
ruling government lawyers say threatens the federal program 
protecting the pensions of 30 million american workers 
the justices said they will decide what authority the pension 
benefit guaranty corporation a federal agency has to order 
employers to restore terminated pension plans 
a federal appeals court limited such authority by setting aside 
the agencys order that ltv corp and its subsidiary ltv steel 
co restore three pension plans with unfunded liabilities of 23 
billion 
the appeal acted on today said the ruling if not overturned 
could make the agency an openended source of industry bailouts 
and could lead to a financial crisis similar to that currently 
facing the governments insurance program for the savings and 
loan industry 
in other action the court 
turned away an appeal by a nebraska state agency that wants to 
test its employees for aids 
the court without comment let stand rulings that blocked the 
eastern nebraska human services agency from imposing mandatory 
blood testing of employees who come into direct contact with the 
mentally retarded people the agency serves 
agreed to use a chicago drug prosecution to consider expanding 
police search powers 
the justices said they will hear arguments that police acting 
without a warrant should be allowed to use evidence seized after 
they were allowed into a mans apartment by his girlfriend 
barred a lawsuit against the christian science church in the 
death of a 15monthold michigan boy who died of meningitis 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that a suit 
against the church and its members over faith healing would violate 
their religious freedom 
rejected an appeal by an american humanist association member 
who says he should have as much right as an ordained minister to 
perform marriage ceremonies 
the court without comment refused to hear arguments that a 
virginia law favoring ministers violates religious freedom and the 
constitutionally required separation of church and state 
refused to hear appeals by three drug manufacturers fighting 
lawsuits over the effects of des a drug once used by pregnant 
women to prevent miscarriages 
the court without comment left intact a new york ruling aimed 
at forcing all manufacturers of the drug to share in paying damages 
for injuries allegedly caused by des 
turned away an appeal by a former beechnut executiv e 
fighting his conviction for selling adulterated apple juice 
the court without comment left intact john f laverys 
sentence of a year and a day in prison and a 100000 fine 
turned down an appeal by james earl ray who is serving a 
99year prison sentence for the assassination of the rev martin 
luther king jr 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that rays rights 
were not violated 20 years ago when he pleaded guilty to 
firstdegree murder 
the pension benefit guaranty corporation modeled after the 
federal deposit insurance corp and the federal savings and loan 
insurance corp is wholly owned by the federal government its 
board of directors is comprised of the secretaries of labor 
treasury and commerce 
the agency protects the pension benefits of the 30 million 
americans who participate in singleemployer defined benefit 
pension plans 
when a pension plan is ended with insufficient money to satisfy 
promised benefits the federal agency becomes the pension plans 
trustee taking over its assets and liabilities the agency then 
pays all benefits workers had earned as of the date the pension 
plan ended 
in fiscal year 1988 the pension benefit guaranty corporation 
paid 3247 million in insured benefits to 113000 retirees who 
participated in 1476 terminated pension plans 
the cost of the pension insurance is paid primarily by employers 
with active pension plans and by employers who terminate 
underfunded pension plans 
the agency has money problems of its own in its most recent 
annual report the pbgc listed liabilities of 4 billion and assets 
of 24 billion 
the dallasbased ltv corp and ltv steel after filing for 
reorganization under federal bankruptcy law in 1986 advised the 
pbgc that they could not and would not fund the three pension plans 
they sponsored the plans which have about 100000 participants 
were terminated in 1987 
in a deal with the united steelworkers of america union 
however ltv steel agreed to what government lawyers contend is a 
followon arrangement under it ltv agreed to make up any 
benefits lost to employees because of the pension plans 
termination those benefits not covered by the federal pension 
insurance program 
the result employees continued to receive the same benefits 
they did before the plans were terminated and payment of unfunded 
pension liabilities was shifted to the pbgc 
ltv was responsible for 75 million in annual supplemental 
retirement benefits and the federal agency was making good on some 
400 million in annual obligations to ltv pensioners 
the pbgc contends such arrangements are abusive and the agency 
ordered ltv to reassume responsibility for the three pension plans 
when ltv refused the agency sought to enforce its order in 
federal court 
a federal judge threw out the pbgcs order for restoration of 
the pension plans and the 2nd us circuit court of appeals upheld 
that ruling last may 12 
federal law reveals no indication that congress intended the 
establishment of successive benefit plans to be a ground for 
restoration the appeals court ruled 
it also said the pbgcs action was arbitrary and capricious 
because it failed to consider the goals of federal bankruptcy and 
labor laws when issuing its restoration order 
the pbgc then sought supreme court review contending that the 
2nd circuit courts ruling places the pension insurance program 
in serious financial jeopardy and ignores what congress attempted 
to achieve in passing the employee retirement income security act 
of 1974 erisa 
other companies will follow ltvs example and use pension 
insurance as a subsidy to reduce costs and gain a competitive 
edge the appeal said 
justice department lawyers sided with the pbgc telling the high 
court the pbgc has reasonably concluded that restoration is an 
appropriate response to the adoption of abusive followon plans 
they said the appeals court ruling threatens to undermine a 
program already seriously in debt 
but lawyers for ltv said congress specifically rejected 
proposed prohibitions on followon plans when substantially 
amending erisa in 1987 
the case is pbgc vs ltv 89390 
</TEXT>
