<TEXT>
the supreme court was urged today to strike 
down a federal judges order doubling local property taxes to pay 
for school desegregation in kansas city mo 
calling the judges 1987 order taxation without 
representation an attorney for the state of missouri h bartow 
farr iii argued that federal courts lack the power to order higher 
taxes even to correct a constitutional violation such as racial 
discrimination in schools 
there is no power to tax period farr told the justices in 
oral arguments 
the state asked the high court to overturn a decision by the 8th 
us circuit court of appeals that upheld the property tax increase 
ordered by us district judge russell clark 
lawyers for both sides spent perhaps a third of the 60minute 
argument session answering questions by several of the justices 
about a possible procedural flaw that could preclude any 
constitutional ruling in the case 
the school district and a group of school children who brought 
the original desegregation case in 1977 urged the court to uphold 
the tax decision the district also maintained that the state 
waited too long to file a supreme court appeal rendering it 
unnecessary for the justices to address the tax issue 
allen snyder an attorney for the district contended that state 
property tax law and local voters must not be allowed to frustrate 
the constitutional rights of kansas citys minority schoolchildren 
to an equal educational opportunity 
snyder said it was dangerously wrong to assume that federal 
courts lack powers to implement their orders to correct 
constitutional violations the courts he said have the powers 
and have the duty to use their equitable discretion to remedy 
such wrongs as racial segregation in schools 
the court is expected to issue a decision in the case by next 
july 
legal scholars and education officials say the courts decision 
could shape future school desegregation plans across the country 
and define the federal courts power to remedy constitutional 
violations involving issues from prison overcrowding to fair 
housing 
clark ordered the tax increase in september 1987 after the local 
school district was unable to pay its share of a more than 400 
million desegregation plan he had approved for capital improvements 
in buildings and establishment of special magnet schools 
state law says local property taxes may be raised only with 
voters approval and in some instances only with a twothirds 
majority district voters had not approved a levy increase since 
1969 with four tax increase proposals rejected in 1986 and 1987 to 
finance the desegregation plan 
in addition to doubling the property tax clark imposed an 
income tax surcharge on those people living or working in the 
school district 
the appeals court struck down the income surcharge in august 
1988 but upheld the district courts authority to order an 
increase in the property tax however the appeals court modified 
the procedure for imposing the higher tax levy 
the appeals court found that state law had effectively prevented 
the school district from levying the necessary taxes to pay for the 
desegregation plan it upheld clarks order as one that set aside 
levy limitations and empowered the elected local school board to 
set the needed tax levels within certain limits 
</TEXT>
