<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday rejected the 
appeal of a member of a secular group who argued that he should 
have the same right to perform marriages as does a priest or rabbi 
roy torcaso of wheaton md won an important victory in 1971 
when the high court held that maryland violated his rights by 
barring him from becoming a statecommissioned notary public 
because he refused to declare a belief in god 
in the current case the justices without comment refused to 
disturb a virginia law favoring ordained ministers in officiating 
at weddings the court rejected torcasos arguments that the law 
violates religious freedom and separation of church and state 
he contended that his constitutional rights are being denied 
because he is a counselor with the american humanist association 
an educational and philosophical organization 
torcaso said he is similar to a priest minister or rabbi and 
should have comparable rights he has been allowed to officiate at 
weddings in other states he said 
however he was rejected in 1988 when he applied to prince 
william county va to perform weddings there 
a virginia judge refused to overturn the county clerks 
rejection 
lawyers with the virginia attorney generals office said the 
state law requires a 500 bond by anyone who is not an ordained 
minister and wants to officiate at a wedding 
ministers are exempt from posting the bond because ordination 
creates a presumption that the officiant is trustworthy and 
responsible lawyers for the state said 
torcaso said he would have been barred under virginia law from 
performing the wedding even if he posted the bond the bond 
requirement he said applies only to judges or others who reside 
in the county where they seek to perform the marriage 
torcaso said other states have similar laws but that they more 
liberally create exemptions that allow nonministers to officiate 
at weddings 
the constitution prohibits states from establishing religious 
qualifications for persons who perform state functions his 
appeal said 
states cannot impose religious affiliation and belief 
requirements upon persons who solemnize marriages 
the case is torcaso vs virginia 89375 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

