<TEXT>
the supreme court in a case closely watched 
by civil rights groups was asked monday to decide whether federal 
courts can order higher taxes to finance school desegregation 
the state of missouri urged the justices to invalidate a federal 
judges 1987 order that doubled local property taxes in kansas 
city saying it was taxation without representation 
h bartow farr iii an attorney for the state argued that 
courts lack the power to impose or authorize higher taxes even to 
correct a constitutional violation such as racial discrimination in 
schools 
there is no power to tax period farr told the justices 
although constitutional issues dominated the 60minute session 
lawyers for both sides answered questions by several justices about 
a possible procedural flaw that could preclude a ruling on the tax 
issue in the case 
the school district and parents of a group of school children 
who brought the original desegregation case in 1977 contend the 
state waited too long to file a supreme court appeal 
the school district asked the court to affirm a decision by the 
8th us circuit court of appeals upholding the property tax 
increase ordered by us district judge russell clark 
the supreme court is expected to issue a decision in the case by 
next july 
allen snyder the school districts attorney said it would be 
dangerously wrong to deny federal courts the broad powers 
needed to implement their orders to correct constitutional 
violations 
striking down the tax order he contended would permit state 
property tax law and local voters to frustrate the constitutional 
rights of kansas citys minority schoolchildren to an equal 
educational opportunity 
federal courts snyder argued have the powers and have the 
duty to use their equitable discretion to remedy constitutional 
wrongs 
several justices questioned whether there were any limits on the 
powers of the federal courts to correct racial segregation in 
schools at one point justice antonin scalia asked if a court 
could order higher taxes to gold plate all the schools 
snyder discounted the justices example but said a courts 
remedy to constitutional violations was limited to what was 
feasible and practicable 
justice anthony kennedy described the judges tax order as a 
drastic remedy and questioned whether the district court should 
have made an explicit finding that higher taxes were the only 
reasonable solution 
the state in response to questions by justice sandra oconnor 
maintained that the judge had failed to consider other options 
such as scaling back the desegregation plan one alternative 
opposed by the state farr conceded was to require the state of 
missouri to pay all of the costs 
clark ordered the tax increase in september 1987 after the local 
school district was unable to pay its share of a 400 million 
desegregation plan he had approved for capital improvements in 
buildings and establishment of special magnet schools 
state law says local property taxes can be raised only with 
voters approval and in some instances only with a twothirds 
majority district voters had not approved a levy increase since 
1969 with four tax increase proposals rejected in 1986 and 1987 to 
finance the desegregation plan 
the appeals court in august 1988 upheld the district courts 
authority to order an increase in the property tax but changed the 
procedure for imposing the higher tax levy in the future 
</TEXT>
