<TEXT>
states have had only modest success in 
classroom reforms although there was a greater effort at improving 
public education in the 1980s than ever before a consortium of 
universities said monday 
state legislators introduced an unsurpassed number of 
educationrelated bills increased state aid and examined the 
findings of hundreds of statelevel task forces and commission 
said the center for policy research in education 
local initiatives had the most progress on restructuring 
schools said the report the progress of reform an appraisal of 
state education initiatives 
the report was based on research conducted in arizona 
california florida georgia minnesota and pennsylvania and used 
as its benchmark goals set forth in a nation at risk the 1983 
landmark government report that prompted efforts to improve 
learning in america 
it is true that high school curricula are more academically 
oriented standards for entering the teaching profession are more 
selective teachers salaries are higher and state and local 
governments have boosted educational funding said the report 
but the reforms met with only modest success in achieving 
their goals the report continued doubts still linger about 
the rigor and challenge of some of the new courses in academic 
subjects the impact of reform on atrisk students the quality of 
teachers and teaching and the equitable funding of schools 
the report said states tended to reject complicated reform 
recommendations in favor of more manageable ones the most popular 
reform of the last five years was increasing graduation 
requirements a relatively uncomplicated procedure the report said 
at least 45 states have modified high school graduation 
requirements since 1980 primarily by increasing the number of 
credits and academic courses needed to earn a diploma it said 
the easy reforms that were adopted have stayed in place the 
report said but more complicated reforms such as teacher 
assessments career ladders and mentor teacher programs have been 
modified or diluted it found 
reforms adopted by most states lacked coherence sending a 
barrage of signals to schools and districts without setting clear 
priorities the study said 
the report said most of the progress resulted from initiatives 
at the local school district level during the 1980s several 
states encouraged school restructuring by providing seed money for 
local experiments but some districts were developing changes 
without state support it said 
the federally funded center for policy research in education is 
a consortium of rutgers michigan state and stanford universities 
and the university of wisconsin at madison 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

