president bush broke ground monday for a 
memorial to slain police officers and said cop killers should pay 
the ultimate price for committing the ultimate crime 
bush drew loud applause from a large crowd that included 
hundreds of police officers widows and other relatives of some of 
the 30000 officers whose names will eventually be carved on 
granite walls at the memorial site 
bush prodded congress to act quickly on the 12 billion 
anticrime package he unveiled last may including stiffer 
penalties for gunrelated crimes limits on semiautomatic weapons 
and no plea bargaining with those who used guns in violent crimes 
it is time to act because these improvements are a vital part 
of our national drug strategy said bush adding before any 
more names are added to that wall the protection you deserve 
should be added to the books 
for cop killers for those who commit the ultimate crime i 
feel strongly that they should pay the ultimate price said the 
president 
the senate is expected to vote later this year on bushs crime 
package the house is awaiting senate action before it takes up the 
measure 
bush who keeps in his desk the shield of a new york city rookie 
policeman eddie byrne murdered last year while protecting a drug 
witness said the toll from police killings rivals those of 
americas overseas wars 
bush made the speech behind bulletproof glass on a stage 
erected at the judiciary square site where the national law 
enforcement officers memorial will be erected 
it will consist of an oval treelined pathway of 
remembrance on a threeacre site with the names of the slain 
police officers on a threefoothigh wall last year alone 161 
federal state and local officers were killed in the line of duty 
bush said it will be a tribute to the thin blue line that 
protects our nation from the evil within 
he singled out several slain officers from the first robert 
marshall a us marshal killed in 1794 serving routine court 
papers in augusta ga to chicago police officer irma ruiz 
killed in september 1988 by a drugcrazed gunman who invaded 
the school where she stood guard to philadelphia officer albert 
valentino shot down last week while investigating a burglary 
ruiz partner gregory jaglowski despite his own wounds 
managed to kill ruiz slayer who had taken three other lives that 
day 
jaglowski joined bush attorney general dick thornburgh and 
craig floyd chairman of the memorial in turning over four shovels 
of dirt for the actual groundbreaking 
the 5 million memorial authorized by a 1984 law unanimously 
passed by congress and signed by president reagan is being built 
with private contributions so far the nonprofit group 
spearheading the drive has raised 4 million including 
contributions from 400000 individuals 
in front row seats at the ceremony were jim brady the former 
white house press secretary wounded in the 1981 attack on reagan 
and his wife sarah now a crusader for gun control 
among the vips on stage were former attorney gen edwin meese 
iii whom bush said had stood strong and tall for law 
enforcement 
