an interpretation of the regulations that allowed it to avoid 
making a politically difficult decision on pierces request 
the regulation states that current and former federal officials 
may be provided representation in civil and congressional 
proceedings and in state criminal proceedings when the actions 
for which representation is requested reasonably appear to have 
been performed within the scope of the employees employment and 
providing representation would otherwise be in the interest of the 
united states 
one would think that clearly on its face we are eligible 
plotkin said and then they have to exercise their discretion as 
to whether or not they want to pay it 
but in an oct 25 letter to hud deputy assistant attorney 
general stephen c bransdorfer said that legal representation by 
the justice department is available only in situations where the 
employee is subject to civil or state criminal proceedings as a 
result of actions taken within the normal scope of that employees 
authority 
if there are no such underlying proceedings then 
representation is not available bransdorfer said 
there are no civil or state criminal proceedings against pierce 
according to bransdorfers determination hud said it was 
recommending that pierces request be denied 
</TEXT>
