<TEXT>
japan which buys more ivory than any other 
country said monday it would join a ban on the ivory trade that is 
intended to protect african elephants 
the ban was adopted oct 17 at a meeting of the 91nation 
convention on trade in endangered species and is to remain in 
effect at least until 1992 
japan had until jan 18 to decide whether to file an appeal 
which would allow it to continue trading ivory with other countries 
that did the same or with the more than 60 nations outside the 
accord 
hajime tsujimoto of the foreign ministrys un office 
acknowledged that international attention on japan as the worlds 
main ivory consumer had played a role in the decision 
he also told reporters the decision did not necessarily mean 
japan was out of the market permanently and that it may import 
if the circumstances in the world change 
if the elephant is removed from the endangered species list he 
said the story will be different 
zimbabwe botswana malawi and mozambique have objected to the 
ban on grounds their elephant herds are not endangered and they 
depend on ivory sales to finance successful conservation by filing 
for exemptions they may continue trade in ivory with other 
countries that do not accept the ban 
a recent census estimated africa now has about 600000 
elephants fewer than half the total of a decade ago 
about 30000 people in japan are employed in the ivory industry 
which carves elephant tusks into ornaments jewelry and personal 
signature seals 
tsujimoto said some might have to find other jobs eventually 
but japan has enough ivory in stock to last about two years 
japan regularly has taken about 40 percent of the worlds ivory 
exports imports totaled 106 tons in 1988 and 143 tons in 1987 
it is to be host of the next meeting of the convention in april 
1992 
tsujimoto said japan would like to study aid to african 
countries for better management of elephant populations 
we are deeply concerned about the rapid decline in the number 
of elephants over the last 10 years he said we believe 
drastic measures should be taken to prevent further decline in the 
number and seek proper protection of the animals 
in hong kong up to 400 ivory traders and carvers marched 
through downtown streets monday to protest the ban adeline li of 
the hong kong and kowloon ivory manufacturers association said 
about 4000 people worked in the industry in hong kong 
</TEXT>
