<TEXT>
security council ambassadors agreed monday 
on a mild resolution that criticizes south africas administration 
in namibia but does not claim that free and fair elections are 
impossible in the territory 
unanimous adoption was likely tuesday after the 15 ambassadors 
consult their capitals said western and third world diplomats on 
the council speaking on condition of anonymity 
black african and nonaligned nations began circulating draft 
resolutions two weeks ago that castigated south africa for alleged 
abuses and prepared to follow up with strong speeches before the 
nov 711 namibian election 
british diplomats said those resolutions invited vetoes from 
more than one of the five permanent security council members the 
united states britain france china and the soviet union 
western diplomats said third world nations were trying to mount 
an 11thhour campaign to boost the electoral chances of the 
southwest africa peoples organization known as swapo 
intense consultations resulted in language agreeable to all 
council members 
this is a watereddown version that causes us no problems 
said aubrey dwyer spokesman for south africa which is not on the 
council theres nothing in there that they can use to declare 
the elections null and void 
the final draft welcomes secretarygeneral javier perez de 
cuellars report on namibia which outlined areas of concern but 
concluded that the territory is headed for a free and fair election 
it demands immediate full and strict compliance by all 
parties concerned in particular south africa in implementing 
council resolutions calling for namibias independence 
it demands that all paramilitary and ethnic forces and commando 
units be disbanded particularly the southwest africa territorial 
force and koevoet a dreaded counterinsurgency unit 
swapo has accused its main competitor the democratic turnhalle 
alliance of hiring koevoet veterans to intimidate proswapo voters 
and break up campaign rallies 
the resolution calls for decommissioning the 1500 south african 
defense force soldiers still in namibia now confined to base under 
un supervision 
it demands repeal of such remaining restrictive and 
discriminatory laws and regulations as inhibit the holding of free 
and fair elections without specifying any 
the resolution endorses perez de cuellars opinion that law ag8 
which establishes a racially segregated society in namibia should 
be repealed 
namibians will vote for a constituent assembly to draft a 
constitution and organize the first independent black 
majorityruled government in the territory of 13 million 
if swapo wins twothirds of the votes it will be able to 
unilaterally write the constitution and organize any form of 
government it chooses 
the former german colony has been governed by south africa since 
1915 
last december south africa signed accords with angola and cuba 
agreeing to cooperate with a un plan for namibias transition to 
independence as cuba withdraws its 50000 troops from angola 
