the case involved contracts for new aluminum skins or outer 
coverings on kc135 refueling tankers and transports from 1974 to 
1986 government investigators alleged that boeing overcharged for 
aluminum raw materials by quoting supplier catalog prices instead 
of their actual costs which were 12 percent to 13 percent less 
during air force contract negotiations boeing is required to 
certify the raw materials prices it quotes are current accurate 
and complete 
an investigation into the case began in 1985 
a federal grand jury in wichita where the division is based 
heard hundreds of hours of testimony and inspected thousands of 
documents for more than nine months before the case was withdrawn 
by prosecutors late last month 
in addition to the other terms of the settlement the agreement 
prohibits boeing from charging any of its costs or legal fees in 
the settlement to government accounts or on future government 
contrcats 
