<TEXT>
vladimir nabokov liked to write standing up 
waking in the early morning and starting work at a blue lectern by 
the afternoon the author would be seated in an armchair a wooden 
board across his lap he usually wrote until bedtime 
with books taking up most of his day letters were written only 
for specific reasons business a line to his publisher or a legal 
matter that required his signature 
there were also notes to his family passionate letters to his 
wife vera when they were apart for a time messages slipped under 
the hotel room door of his son dmitri in montreaux switzerland 
words of encouragement to his brother kirill an aspiring poet 
not every writer could be creative at all times but as dmitri 
nabokov said in a recent interview even the most casual memo by 
his father was something special graced by the touch that produced 
lolita the gift ada and many others 
it was a thrill i loved it recalled nabokov 55 who 
helped compile the letters of vladimir nabokov 19401977 
harcourt brace jovanovich 2995 
i knew that as in his fiction around the corner of every 
sentence there would be a nice little surprise a linguistic 
surprise he said 
whether he was writing to a publisher writing to a son 
making up a grocery list there was always something original in 
how he phrased it the receptors of my spinal cord were always 
ready for his language 
nabokov admits that a certain settling of accounts was in mind 
upon issuing his late fathers letters vladimir nabakovs stern 
precise image represented just one side his son insists consider 
what the author wrote to vera in may 1937 after his recovery from a 
recent illness 
you know now i can tell you frankly the indescribable 
torments in february before these treatments drove me to the 
border of suicide a border i was not authorized to cross because 
i had you in my luggage my love is it really true that i shall 
soon see you if fate does not let me down 
try not to worry too much my love we shall be together soon 
anyway tell mother i embrace her and am not writing her only 
because i am spending all my epistolary energy on you 
lolita of course touched off dozens of letters ranging 
from amusement to anger as frightened publishers suggested changes 
or backed away and governments attempted censorship 
nabokov knew his story of a middleaged mans passionate affair 
with a 12yearold girl would create controversy and this 1950s 
best seller became the usually apolitical authors most passionate 
cause 
on march 6 1956 he wrote to morris bishop chairman of the 
department of romance literature at cornell university where 
nabokov also taught 
i know that lolita is my best book so far i calmly lean on 
my conviction that it is a serious work of art and that no court 
could prove it to be lewd and libertine 
all categories raid of course into one another a comedy of 
manners written by a fine poet may have its lewd side but lolita 
is a tragedy pornography is not an image plucked out of context 
pornography is an attitude and an intention the tragic and the 
obscene exclude each other 
those writers nabokov found inferior are spared nothing poet 
ts eliot and author thomas mann are dismissed as big fakes 
nobelist saul bellow is a mediocrity poet ezra pound is 
disgusting and entirely secondrate 
critic edmund wilson a onetime supporter feuded openly with 
nabokov in the 1950s after many years of a warm friendship these 
two great literary figures drifted apart 
it started on a professional level with nabokov attacking 
wilsons attempts at russian translation and ended with bitter 
personal attacks in the early 1970s shortly before the critics 
death 
as you perhaps know the warm friendship between ew and vn 
which began in 1941 was later obliterated by minor and major 
clashes nabokov would sadly note 
he preferred the russian poet alexander pushkin spending years 
on the english translation of his novel in verse eugene onegin 
nabokov also admired james joyce whose ulysses was labeled 
pornographic as well and marcel proust author of the classic 
remembrance of things past whose gift for intricate detail had 
a powerful influence 
proust was very visual and chromatic in his approach and so 
was father dmitri nabokov said father in his youth wanted to 
a painter at the age of 15 he received lessons in the house he 
had talent but his teacher read the first of my fathers attempts 
at poetry and prose and said you have to a writer or a poet 
vladimir nabokov the son of a prominent liberal in 
prerevolutionary russia was born 1899 in st petersburg now 
leningrad he read tolstoy and turgenev as a child played chess 
and collected butterflies a lifelong fascination 
unhappy with the bolshevik government he emigrated in 1919 and 
lived in several countries before settling in the united states in 
1940 twenty years later the author and vera moved to switzerland 
where they remained until his death in 1977 vera nabokov still 
lives in montreaux 
he was a wonderfully warm guy said dmitri nabokov who 
translated several of his fathers books he was my best friend 
as is mother but he was intransigent with bad art and secondhand 
ideas intransigent with those who mutilated his art and very 
very jealous with his time 
his time and strength were finite he felt he had a gift that 
he had to utilize to the fullest and he wanted to write he did not 
go on bookstore tours and was very parsimonious in giving 
interviews 
in 1964 nabokov did agree to a rare interview and conducted it 
in even rarer style the reporter filled a stack of paper with 
questions and handed them to nabokov who walked to his lectern and 
composed the answers always his son observed the author knew how 
he best communicated 
in his own words i think like a genius i write like a 
distinguished author i speak like a child he also said that he 
was a wretched public speaker which wasnt true he was a 
wonderful speaker he did a lot of offthenabokovuffing as he 
called it 
he was such a precisionist with language he felt that 
everything he published should be up to the best level or the right 
thought 
</TEXT>
