<TEXT>
petroleum producers arent doing enough to 
protect the environment from potentially hazardous oil field wastes 
and in some cases arent using common sense an environmental 
protection agency official said 
the oil and natural gas industry is way behind in waste 
management both in the volume and the toxicity of wastes 
generated robert tonetti acting deputy director for the epas 
waste management division said sunday 
tonetti also said the industry needs more regulation at all 
government levels especially in the area of commercialized waste 
management facilities 
he spoke to the independent petroleum association of america 
the conference in san antonio lasts through tuesday 
oil producers in some cases are not using common sense 
when disposing of exploration and production wastes allowing 
nonhazardous materials to be mixed with toxic chemicals tonetti 
said 
if not disposed of properly oil field wastes threaten public 
health and safety because wastes generated during oil exploration 
and production can wipe out groundwater supplies and contaminate 
soil tonetti said 
under the epas resource conservation and recovery act those 
wastes are exempt from hazardous waste regulations 
but the act applies the exemption only to drilling fluids 
produced waters and other wastes associated with crude oil or 
natural gas production 
the exemption does not include unused chemicals spent solvents 
empty drums used lubrication oils or acidic cleaners these 
chemicals sometimes get mixed with nonhazardous wastes and create 
a hazardous substance and a health risk tonetti said 
a lot of misunderstanding exists among producers about what is 
exempt and what is not he said 
</TEXT>
