<TEXT>
two more wall street brokerages said monday they 
would limit their program trading joining other major firms that 
have backed away from the strategy under pressure following the 
recent stock market volatility 
merrill lynch amp co said that effective immediately it would not 
execute index arbitrage for its clients kidder peabody amp co said 
it had ceased index arbitrage for its own accounts but would 
continue using the strategy for its customers 
the announcements followed similar moves by large brokerages 
last week on friday morgan stanley group inc and bear stearns amp 
co two of the biggest users of program trading said they would 
stop using index arbitrage to trade for their own accounts 
painewebber group inc stopped using all forms of the strategy 
index arbitrage is a computerized trading strategy aimed at 
profiting on brief and minute differences between prices of stocks 
and stockindex futures which are traded on chicago futures 
exchanges 
the trading tactic in which millions of shares can be bought or 
sold in seconds often is geared to make shortterm profits during 
excitable markets critics say it can accentuate market movements 
leading to sharp price swings such as the 190point drop in the dow 
jones industrial average on oct 13 
merrill lynch halted index arbitrage for its own account nearly 
two years ago following the black monday stock market crash which 
critics said was worsened by program trading 
in mondays statement merrill chairman william a schreyer and 
president daniel p tully said the causes of excess market 
volatility are far more complex than any particular computer 
trading strategy 
but they conceded that index arbitrage has been clearly 
identified in the investing publics mind as a contributing factor 
to excess market volatilty 
merrill would stop executing such trades until the firm is 
satisfied that effective controls are in place the statement 
read 
kidder was the third most active index arbitrage firm during 
september trading 346 million shares with the strategy during the 
month while merrill lynch ranked seventh with 128 million shares 
according to the new york stock exchange morgan stanley led all 
firms with volume of 531 million shares 
the brokerage houses have come under considerable pressure to 
eliminate the strategy last week kemper financial services inc 
and keystone group inc two major institutional investors said 
they would no longer buy or sell stock through brokerages that 
conduct index arbitrage phoenix mutual life insurance co of 
hartford conn followed suit friday 
on monday the investment management firm neuberger amp berman 
took out a fullpage new york times advertisement imploring stop 
the numbers racket on wall street the ad urged investors to 
voice their concerns in writing to securities and exchange 
commission chairman richard breeden and federal reserve chairman 
alan greenspan 
according to new york stock exchange figures program trading of 
all kinds accounted for a record 138 percent of average daily 
volume in september the most since the exchange began keeping such 
figures in july 1988 
</TEXT>
